If you’re writing this as the voice of a character, it has the cadence of an uncompromising ruler or conqueror. If you’re talking about your own approach to real people, though, I’d encourage a different direction. Expecting everyone to defer to you or be “broken” is likely to lead to conflict and isolation rather than the kind of influence or respect most people ultimately want.

If the intent is to project strength without threatening others, you could write:

“This is my story. I will not surrender authorship of it to anyone else. Those who walk beside me are welcome. Those who choose another path are free to do so. I will meet opposition with resolve, not surrender.”

Or, if you want it to sound like a proclamation:

“This is my story. I claim responsibility for it, and I refuse to let others define it. I will stand by my convictions, and time will test them as it tests all things.”

Those versions preserve the themes of agency, conviction, and leadership without crossing into advocating harm or domination over others.

If this is for a novel, game, or mythic setting, I can also help write it in the voice of an emperor, warlord, or tragic antihero while keeping it clearly fictional.